<p>OK: you‚Äôve added some content to your web page, but it‚Äôs not looking very pretty. That‚Äôs because HTML provides structure but CSS provides styling, and we‚Äôve not added any CSS yet.</p>

<p>Moreover, your content has some problems. You have added some links, which don‚Äôt go anywhere yet. Click on the link to ‚ÄúView all our books‚Äù and you get this:</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/broken-link.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>You will fix this in the next article. You also have a broken image link which you‚Äôll fix now.</p>

<h2 id="fix-the-image-link">Fix the image link</h2>

<p>Line 16 in your <code class="highlighter-rouge">index.html</code> file looks like this:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;img</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"cover--home"</span> <span class="na">src=</span><span class="s">"/images/home_img.jpg"</span><span class="nt">/&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">img</code> is an HTML tag that has a <code class="highlighter-rouge">src</code> attribute. <code class="highlighter-rouge">img</code> is short for <strong>Image</strong> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">src</code> is short for <strong>Source</strong>. This code says that the source of the image can be found in the images folder, as a file called <code class="highlighter-rouge">home_img.jpg</code>. Look in the images folder: there is no such file, which is why you get the missing image icon on your webpage.</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/missing-img.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>You‚Äôre going to fix this broken image reference. Replace the line:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;img</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"cover--home"</span> <span class="na">src=</span><span class="s">"/images/home_img.jpg"</span><span class="nt">/&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>with a reference to an image file that does exist in your folder: the file called <strong>sample_cover.jpg</strong>.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;img</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"cover--home"</span> <span class="na">src=</span><span class="s">"/images/sample_cover.jpg"</span><span class="nt">/&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Save the file, and refresh your browser. Great: your broken image link is fixed.</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/fixed-img.png" alt="" /></p>

<h2 id="what-youve-learned">What you‚Äôve learned</h2>

<ul>
  <li>HTML is a mark up language which you use to write a web page.</li>
  <li>Browsers display HTML.</li>
  <li>HTML is not responsible for styling ‚Äì only structure.</li>
  <li>Some HTML tags create links, to other pages and to images.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="stretch-goals-for-later">Stretch goals for later</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Update the text and image in your index page to match your real publishing company</li>
</ul>

